<div class="mktEditable" id="product-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; ">
<p style="color: #666666; font-weight: 300;"><img style="display: block;" title="McCoy" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/pivotal/images/Jaime.png" alt="Jaime" width="130" height="172" align="right" constrain="true" imagepreview="false" /></p> 
<table style="border-collapse: collapse;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"> 
<tbody> 
<tr> 
<td height="15'"></td> 
</tr> 
<tr> 
<td> <p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; margin: 0; font-size: 30px; line-height: 1.2em; color: #000000; font-weight: 300; text-transform: uppercase;">The beginner's guide to pks&nbsp;</p> </td> 
</tr> 
</tbody> 
</table> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><a style="color: #00ae9e; text-decoration: none;" href="#author-socialcast-profile"></a><a href="#author-socialcast-profile" style="color: #008774; text-decoration: none;">Jaime Gonzalez Aguilar</a><span style="color: #666666; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 300; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-size-adjust: auto; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;">, Senior Platform Architect</span><br /></p>
</div>
<div class="mktEditable" id="product-entry" style="padding-right:40px; ">
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">We recently announced Pivotal Container Service (aka, PKS), and ever since, there has been a flood of interest from all corners of the industry. The enterprise is very interested in containers, but because they've faced common hurdles in getting containers into production, they're keen to understand how PKS can help them. Solving this will bring new ways for Pivotal to create value.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">When we explain PKS, we talk about different developer abstractions and the importance of choosing the right tool for the right workload. In a nutshell, PKS is a commercial solution for enterprises to run container workloads from any infrastructure—your container runtime solution, which brings important measures of reliability and ease-of-use to anywhere you run them.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">PKS also cracks open the door to new sales opportunities for Pivotal, as we'll soon be able to address a set of workloads that were more difficult to manage with Pivotal Cloud Foundry's (PCF) Elastic Runtime—soon to be renamed Pivotal Application Service—alone.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">Specifically, PKS will help enterprises that already run workloads directly on an IaaS, or on another Kubernetes distribution, to do the following:</p> 
<ul> 
<li>Run pre-packaged, containerized workloads delivered as containers by other teams or ISVs (independent software vendors).<br /></li> 
<li>Run stateful services which use Persistent Storage such as MongoDB, Cassandra, Spark, Elastic Search, and CouchDB.<br /></li> 
<li>Run legacy workloads more easily, and even become a stepping stone to modernizing these workloads and making them suitable to run in PCF’s ERT.</li> 
<li>Run workloads that require higher levels of customization (e.g., multiple ports), when developer teams want more control in how applications are deployed and handled by PCF.</li> 
</ul> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">So what constitutes PKS? Jointly developed between Pivotal, VMWare, and Google, PKS provides the control plane for provisioning and managing Cloud Foundry Container Runtime (CFCR—and&nbsp;<a href="https://cloudfoundry.org/cloud-foundry-launches-container-runtime-default-container-deployment-method-cloud-foundry-using-kubernetes-bosh/" target="_blank" style="color: #00ae9e; text-decoration: none;">until very recently </a>was known as&nbsp;Kubo). And what is CFCR? CFCR is an OSS project launched by Pivotal and Google, and incubated since June in the <a href="https://www.cloudfoundry.org/foundation/" target="_blank" style="color: #00ae9e; text-decoration: none;">Cloud Foundry Foundation</a>. As a uniform way to instantiate, deploy, and manage highly available Kubernetes clusters on any cloud, it's a natural starting point for PKS. <br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><strong>Pivotal and the BOSH Factor</strong><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">Kubernetes lacks an underpinning component to manage the deployment and lifecycle of the infrastructure resources to run a cluster. Both CFCR and PKS share the same substrate as PCF, which is BOSH, a key aspect that gives PKS and PCF the same guarantees around security, availability, health management, operational efficiency. These capabilities are extremely valuable to enterprises, helping them solve what have been common stumbling blocks in operationalizing Kubernetes. BOSH to the rescue!</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><strong>Google and Synchronized Releases</strong></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><strong></strong><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">Another key feature of PKS is release-level synchronization with Google Container Engine (GKE). This means PKS is always on the same Kubernetes release as the Google Container Engine. It gives us an edge over other Kubernetes-based platforms (such as OpenShift) that lag behind because they run on older versions.<br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><strong>On-Demand, and VMware Icing<br /><br /></strong>There's more. PKS provides additional out-of-the-box capabilities to make it the best place to run your containers in the enterprise. Not only can you deploy Kubernetes clusters, you can do it on demand, via the On Demand Broker (ODB), letting developers create dedicated and isolated clusters for specific needs.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">The other key ease-of-use piece is how PKS integrates CFCR with VMware:.</p> 
<ul> 
<li><span style="font-size: 15px;">With VMware's NSX, to safely create and manage the Kubernetes networking model, and to provide additional security and isolation for the cluster workloads.</span><br /></li> 
<li><span style="font-size: 15px;">With Harbor, an enterprise-class container registry server, with vulnerability scanning, identity management, and support for multiple registries</span></li> 
</ul> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">VMware is further working on integrating PKS with its technologies in the VMware stack, forming what we could refer to as VMware-PKS. (So many names!)</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/PKS Portfolio.png" alt="PKS image" width="530" height="284" constrain="true" imagepreview="false" border="" /><br /><br />In the end, every layer from the PKS portfolio (CFCR, PKS, V-PKS) can be used independently of the other external layers, giving the enterprise confidence to run container workloads in production, anywhere, with ease</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">.</p>
</div><a href="#top" style="color:#00ae9e; font-size:14px; text-decoration:none; padding-top:20px; display:block;font-weight:bold">Back to the Top</a></td>
