<div class="mktEditable" id="culture-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; ">
<p><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/pivotal/images/Roshni.png" alt="Roshni Champati" width="130" height="172" align="right" constrain="true" imagepreview="false" /></p> 
<table style="border-collapse: collapse;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"> 
<tbody> 
<tr> 
<td height="15'"></td> 
</tr> 
<tr> 
<td> <p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; margin: 0; font-size: 30px; line-height: 1.2em; color: #000000; font-weight: 300; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-e54802cd-f4c7-eff0-3b15-652f5e7290fe"><span>why support and community knowledge matter</span></span></p> </td> 
</tr> 
</tbody> 
</table> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><a style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;" href="#author-socialcast-profile">Roshni Champati</a>, Senior Program Manager, Knowledge Center, Palo Alto</p>
</div>
<div class="mktEditable" id="culture-entry" style="padding-right:40px; "> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">At Pivotal, we know how a box, product, or a container will behave—we test early and often. But when a customer implements thousands of instances of boxes in a unique, highly distributed architecture, things get less predictable. During major releases, codebases can be a bit like human beings—with mood swings that cannot always be anticipated. Everyone wants a product to be great and bug-free, but like life, products have ups and downs.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">This is a familiar theme for enterprises across industries as they seek to become cloud-native. Pivotal is helping the enterprise achieve massive gains in developer velocity and operator reliability. However, many customers also find that the journey itself is a fast-forward process to a whole set of unfamiliar authentication and gateway protocols.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">Many financial, health, and insurance services, among others, still run largely on top of on-premise datacenters. Crossing the chasm to hybrid and public cloud disrupts monoliths that do not scale efficiently. Crossing the chasm to hybrid and public cloud disrupts monoliths that do not scale efficiently. So we're not interested in not just helping customers set-up, but also run sustainable architectures, and to be constinuously successful with Pivotal products. "Day 2"— and any day afterward—matters, and that's why how we approach customer support.<br /><br />Pivotal Support is evolving to an agile Pivotal model. We're focusing support on help desks and support teams that resolve incidents faster, helping customers achieve seamless, continuous improvements as they refactor architectures and scale out new cloud services. Pivotal Support helps developers, operators, and administrators that build apps and run operations, to maintain concurrency, disposability, and developer product parity.<br /><br /><strong>Knowledge Sharing is Communication is Continuous Learning<br /><br /></strong> Good communication is critical. We listen to the expanding Pivotal customer community, and offer advance knowledge on what works, or how to resolve immediate problems. In areas where it applies, we make that knowledge repeatable. Customers can resolve things faster and more autonomously.</p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;"><br /></p> 
<p><img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/cloud-joke-cartoon.jpg" alt="cloud-joke" height="491" width="530" constrain="true" imagepreview="false" /></p> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">Pivotal Support <a href="https://sites.google.com/a/pivotal.io/inside-pivotal/departments/pivotal-support/Knowledge-Centered-Support" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">Knowledge Management</a>, Technical Support, and product R&amp;D teams have collaborated to spearhead a collaboration with the Cloud Foundry document team to cover and document around known issues both before and after we released Pivotal Cloud Foundry 1.12. They can be found in the <a href="https://docs.pivotal.io/pivotalcf/1-12/pcf-release-notes/opsmanager-rn.html#known-issues" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">Known Issues</a> section of Pivotal Docs and Knowledge Base articles. The <a href="https://discuss.pivotal.io/hc/en-us" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">Pivotal Knowledge Base</a> routinely gets 4,000 views each weekday, and 90,000+ views a month.<br /><br />Here's a sample of what you can find:<br /></p> 
<ul> 
<li><a href="https://discuss.pivotal.io/hc/en-us/articles/115012374148" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">Permissions error when running BOSH commands on the Director</a>.<br /></li> 
<li><a href="https://discuss.pivotal.io/hc/en-us/articles/115012475527" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">Config server error when redeploying Elastic Runtime with BBR.</a></li> 
<li><a href="https://discuss.pivotal.io/hc/en-us/articles/115012480807" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">SSO memory error when deploying to Pivotal Cloud Foundry 1.12.</a></li> 
<li><a href="https://discuss.pivotal.io/hc/en-us/articles/115012474187" target="_blank" style="color: #87c876; text-decoration: none;">CredHub fails to start when deploying Pivotal Cloud Foundry 1.11 and 1.12.</a></li> 
</ul> 
<p style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #666666; font-size: 15px; line-height: 18px; margin: 0px;">This is not about favoring documentation over testing and process, but winnowing down the list of unexpected hitches. As customers bring ever larger Pivotal product implementations to unique environments, documentation helps keep them successful throughout its lifecycle.<br /><br />In the end, with something this new, the knowledge base we're building is also about building enduring trust with customers.</p> 
</div><a href="#top" style="color:#87c876; font-size:14px; text-decoration:none; padding-top:20px; display:block;font-weight:bold">Back to the Top</a></td>
</tr>
